      "type": "html",
      "text": "\nThe intuitive approach to solving this problem is to have each philosopher first pick up his left chopstick then his right. However, this will lead to deadlock as all four of the necessary and sufficient conditions for deadlock come into play: blocking shared resources (chopsticks), no pre-emption (one philosopher cannot ask his adjacents to drop their chopsticks), holding while acquiring (a philosopher holds his left chopstick before trying to pick up his right) and circular waiting (each philosopher shares chopsticks).",
      "id": "5798e878ccc7dba71ac0cf07ee589091"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "text": "\nClearly our naive scheme doesn't quite work as planned. However, as all conditions for deadlock are both necessary and sufficient, we should be able to prevent the deadlock by breaking any one of the conditions above. ",
      "id": "b1c9429638cd83e82c833ab2654382fd"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "text": "\nAn obvious way around this is that philosophers who can't get both chopsticks should put them down, go back to thinking and try again later. This is trying to break the third deadlock property above: 'holding while acquiring'. However, if the philosophers are unlucky and keep doing this all in synchrony, none of them will actually get to eat! Each will drop a chopstick only to try and grab it once more. This solution breaks the problem of deadlock but in doing so, we have introduced another potential problem - that of livelock. The philosophers will not grind to a halt but instead can just go round in circles trying to decide who should have the chopsticks but never getting anywhere. The philosophers won't eat and will starve (quite literally!). This solution isn't much good either.",
